So each row represents one customer. Spending score potentially is a score for how much money is spend in the mall

We have no missing datapoints, distributions look ok for the type of data it contains (always positive, so slighlty right skewed)

Question 2

We are interested in creating a marketing campaign to target customers based on their spending score and annual income. Select an appropriate value for k and perform k-means clustering to find if there are meaningful clusters in the data to target the customers.

Question 3

Visualise the clustering for your chosen value of k.

Based on this graph, we see 5 groups of customers: Within group of customers that have a high annual income (mean income 86 and 88), there is a group with a high spending score, and a group with low spending score.

This same pattern is visible for customers with a low annual income (mean 25 and 26k)

Only customers with an average income (55k), sahre a similar spending score with a mean of 49

The different genders give the same clustering pattern.

Question 4

Do you think the clustering seems a good fit for this data?

Yes, since the grouping of 5 clusters stays +/- present across visualisations of different variables.
